{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533926"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14876"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14876"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.23,0.37,0.13,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7567"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95235"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1141"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2880"},{"type":"tags","id":"2897"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"},{"type":"tags","id":"12756"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18498"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45651"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old Indigenous man is admitted to hospital from a remote community with three weeks of worsening shortness of breath and peripheral oedema. His medical history is unknown. He brings with him a box of medications from home which includes perindopril, amlodipine, calcium carbonate, calcitriol, linagliptin and furosemide, though he admits he doesn\u0027t always take all his medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears short of breath at rest. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 162/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 29/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has bilateral pitting oedema to the mid-thigh and crepitations to the mid-zones bilaterally on chest auscultation. He remains anuric even despite high-doses of furosemide, and a decision is made to commence haemodialysis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions most likely contributed to this patient\u0027s need for dialysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute rheumatic fever","Essential hypertension","Diabetes mellitus","IgA glomerulonephritis","Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of end-stage kidney disease requiring dialysis initiation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is the leading cause of end-stage kidney disease in Indigenous Australians, accounting for approximately 71% of new dialysis starts. This reflects the high prevalence of type 2 diabetes in Indigenous Australians, often diagnosed at a younger age and with more rapid progression to complications. The presence of linagliptin (a diabetes medication) in the patient\u0027s Webster pack supports this diagnosis. The mainstay of management is optimum diabetic control, and use of anti-proteinuric agents (if appropriate) such as ACE inhibitors/ARBs and SGLT2 inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEssential hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to 5% of new dialysis starts in Indigenous Australians, although it is worth noting that many patients with diabetic kidney disease will also have co-existing hypertension +/- significant impact on kidney function. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlomerulonephritis contributes to 7% of new dialysis starts in Indigenous Australians, with \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E being a more common form of glomerulonephritis across both the general population, and also amongst Indigenous Australians. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute rheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E, while more common in Indigenous populations, rarely causes kidney failure as its primary manifestation. Its main complications are cardiac.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited condition that affects all ethnic groups equally but is a comparatively less common cause of end-stage kidney disease in Indigenous Australians.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diabetic kidney disease is the leading cause of end-stage kidney disease in Indigenous Australians starting dialysis.","Early recognition and management of diabetes and its complications is crucial in preventing progression to end-stage kidney disease.","Social determinants of health significantly impact the development and progression of chronic kidney disease in Indigenous Australians."],"references":["1.10 kidney disease - AIHW Indigenous HPF. In: Australian Institute of Health and Welfare [Internet]. 2023. Available at: https://www.indigenoushpf.gov.au/measures/1-10-kidney-disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95235"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14876"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95235"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T13:07:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:07:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7567"}},